In triangle $ABC$, $AB = AC = 5$ and $BC = 6$.  Let $O$ be the circumcenter of triangle $ABC$.  Find the area of triangle $OBC$.

[asy]
unitsize(0.6 cm);

pair A, B, C, O;

A = (0,4);
B = (-3,0);
C = (3,0);
O = circumcenter(A,B,C);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(circumcircle(A,B,C));
draw(B--O--C);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$O$", O, N);
[/asy]

inference:
Since $AB=AC$, triangle $ABC$ is isosceles, so the altitude from $A$ to $BC$ bisects $BC$.  Let $D$ be the foot of the altitude from $A$ to $BC$.

[asy]
unitsize(0.6 cm);

pair A, B, C, O, D;

A = (0,4);
B = (-3,0);
C = (3,0);
O = circumcenter(A,B,C);
D = (B + C)/2;

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(circumcircle(A,B,C));
draw(B--O--C);
draw(A--D);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$O$", O, N);
label("$D$", D, S);
[/asy]

Then $BD=CD=3$.  Also, $AD$ is the perpendicular bisector of $BC$, so $OD$ is also a radius of the circumcircle of triangle $ABC$.  Since $AB=AC=5$, by the Pythagorean Theorem,
\[AD = \sqrt{AB^2 - BD^2} = \sqrt{5^2 - 3^2} = 4.\]Therefore, the area of triangle $OBC$ is
\[\frac{1}{2} \cdot BC \cdot OD = \frac{1}{2} \cdot 6 \cdot 4 = \boxed{12}.\]

